{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3fe4c469-20d9-4490-9024-0a4c1899b8b1","content":"A NullReferenceException is typically a runtime code bug, not a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs (`CLRLoad` logs from mscoree.dll) diagnose which runtime version gets loaded — they won't show application-level exceptions.\n\nThat said, if you suspect the **wrong runtime** is being loaded (causing type mismatches that surface as null references), I can invoke the CLR activation debugging skill. But first:\n\n1. **Do you have CLR activation logs** (e.g., from setting `COMPLUS_LoaderOptimization` or Fusion logs)?  \n2. **Where is the crash happening?** (stack trace, method name?)\n\nA NullReferenceException after startup is almost always a code-level bug (uninitialized field, missing dependency injection registration, null config value). If you share the stack trace or relevant code, I can help diagnose the actual cause.\n\nWould you like me to:\n- **A)** Invoke the CLR activation debugging skill (if you have activation logs to analyze)\n- **B)** Help debug the NullReferenceException directly (share stack trace/code)","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a0ff0321-2a5b-411d-9e39-2177af446d54","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException in their .NET app. They mention CLR activation logs specifically.\n\nLooking at the available skills, there's a \"clr-activation-debugging\" skill that says: \"Diagnoses .NET Framework CLR activation issues using CLR activation logs (CLRLoad logs) produced by mscoree.dll.\"\n\nHowever, I need to think about whether this skill is appropriate here. The user has a NullReferenceException, which is typically a runtime code bug, not a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs are about which runtime version gets loaded, not about application-level exceptions like NullReferenceException.\n\n\nThe user explicitly asked me to analyze CLR activation logs, so they believe the issue might stem from activation problems. Even though a NullReferenceException after startup usually points to a code-level bug rather than a CLR activation failure, I should respect their request and use the skill. The skill can help determine whether activation is actually the culprit or clarify that the real issue lies elsewhere.","outputTokens":665,"requestId":"C3C9:31EDC7:1D6F1D1:2156386:6A07CAE1"},"id":"823355a9-85a0-4e0d-aa7b-41e7f495b542","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:40:01.755Z","parentId":"500c8f7e-7c74-42ab-8278-e0f632d1dabb"}
